## Existing Bevy grass crates

There is a `bevy_procedural_grass` crate that generates grass positions over meshes and advertises GPU instancing, distance/frustum culling and LOD, but its published release targets **Bevy 0.12**, so it should be treated as an architectural reference rather than directly adopted for Bevy 0.19. ([Crates.io][5])

I did not find a mature, widely adopted, turnkey grass plugin already updated for Bevy 0.19. Bevy’s ecosystem currently provides the rendering building blocks rather than a definitive production grass solution. The official Bevy assets directory is the main registry for community plugins, but compatibility should be verified per crate. ([Bevy][6])

## Recommendation for your engine

Build this in stages:

```text
Phase 1
CPU-generated grass-cluster mesh per terrain chunk

Phase 2
Vertex-shader wind and biome-controlled density

Phase 3
Automatic instancing with one entity per grass patch

Phase 4
Distance LOD and patch-level frustum culling

Phase 5
Interaction bending and persistent disturbance maps

Phase 6
Compute-generated positions, GPU culling and indirect rendering
```

The ideal final architecture is:

```text
World atlas and terrain surface
        ↓
CPU creates deterministic ecological candidate set
        ↓
GPU instance buffer stores visible grass
        ↓
Vertex shader handles wind and interaction
        ↓
Chunk/patch LOD controls density
        ↓
Terrain material replaces geometry at long range
```

That will integrate cleanly with your biome fields, voxel terrain edits, streamed chunks and future vegetation simulation without making grass part of the authoritative voxel representation.

